> [[MAT 258 Hub - Discrete Mathematics|MAT 258 Hub - Discrete Mathematics]], [[Conditional Probability with coins Example|Conditional Probability with coins Example]]

Given event $A$ with $P(A)>0$, the probability of $B$ given $A$ (probability of $B$ knowing $A$, probability of $B$ conditioned on $A$) is
$$
\begin{align*}
&\textcolor{gray}{\text{Conditional probability formula:}} \\
&\boxed{P(B|A) = \frac{P(A\cap B)}{P(A)}}
\end{align*}
$$

Which is saying the probability of B given A is the probability of A and B divided by the probability of a:

### Remarks
1) Conditioning on $A$ reduces the state space
2) Probability now depends on new information we're given, namely $A$
3) $P(A)>0$, so as to not divide by zero.
4) If $A$ and $B$ are independent: $$P(B|A) = \frac{P(A\cap B)}{P(A)} = \frac{P(A)P(B)}{P(A)} = P(B)$$
   Probability of $A$ has no effect on $B$, which tracks
5) Multiply both sides of $(*)$ by $P(A)$ $$\boxed{P(A\cap B) = P(A)P(B|A)}$$
   This will be useful to compute probability for 2 step experiments.
